Harborside Refrigerated Services personnel circulate throughout the facility, taking note of unusual conditions in any portion of any of the system several times each day.  If a leak is detected or observed by any Harborside Refrigerated Services employee, it is immediately reported to the Maintenance Engineer.  Action is promptly taken to mitigate the leak so normal operations can resume.

Engineering Measures

Harborside Refrigerated Services was designed and constructed in accordance with ammonia refrigeration industry safety and design standards (Uniform Mechanical Code) and includes several monitoring and sensing devices.  These devices will activate alarms when conditions vary beyond designated limits.  The alarms are indicated on local instrumentation panels, the facility-wide alarm system, and remote alarms at the facility.  Some alarms will be responded to manually while others are interlocked to another device.  The ammonia refrigeration system at the facility is controlled and monitored using the following:

| process indicators and alarms;
| inspections;
| preventative maintenance;
| personnel training;
| incident investigations; and
| ammonia gas sensor.

Each of these items is detailed in the ?Prevention Program 3" section of this RMPlan.

In addition to the Uniform Mechanical Code, and ASME standards applicable at the time of construction for piping and vessels (ASME Section VIII Division I Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code, and ASME B31.5 Refrigeration Piping Code), the facility will operate in accordance with the International Institute of Ammonia Refrigeration (IIAR) guidelines.


